Arrays in php
    Types of arrays
     1. Indexed arrays
       - This is normal arry we just define using array() function in which every 
         position we place our elements!
         e.g $friends = array("Harold", "Carolina", "Miguel");
       - To index this array we use numbers from 0 e.g $friends[0]
     2. Associative arrays
       - This array is analog of "dictionary" or hashMap. We place a set of key/value pairs
         e.g $family = array("Harold" => "Father", "Carolina" => "Mother", "Miguel" => "Son" );
       - To index this array we use the key e.g $family["Harold"]
     3. Multidimensional arrays
       - This is just an array of >3n. Where we can assoaciate multiple values. In other 
         words are just high-level arrays
       - To define this kind of arrays, we just nest array inside another arrays() calls
         e.g $cars = array (
                            array("Volvo",22,18),
                            array("BMW",15,13),
                            ...=


    count() function:
     - This returns the length of an array
    
    Indexing arrays:
     - We can index our arrays just using square brackets. The index 

-- example 
<?php 
    $family = array("Harold" => "Father", "Carolina" => "Mother", "Miguel" => "Son" );
    $family["Harold"] = "Dad";
    // echo $family["Harold"];
    // echo  count($family);
    echo $family[$_POST["name"]];
?>